explanation:
\textbf{Step 1 — Identify months where Product Q's sales strictly exceed Product P's sales:}

\begin{itemize}
\item Jan: P = 60, Q = 50 $\Rightarrow$ Q $<$ P (excluded)
\item Feb: P = 75, Q = 55 $\Rightarrow$ Q $<$ P (excluded)
\item Mar: P = 90, Q = 65 $\Rightarrow$ Q $<$ P (excluded)
\item Apr: P = 80, Q = 95 $\Rightarrow$ Q $>$ P \textbf{(included)}
\item May: P = 70, Q = 85 $\Rightarrow$ Q $>$ P \textbf{(included)}
\item Jun: P = 85, Q = 60 $\Rightarrow$ Q $<$ P (excluded)
\end{itemize}

The qualifying months are \textbf{April} and \textbf{May}.

\textbf{Step 2 — Calculate profit per unit:}
\begin{itemize}
\item Product P: Profit per unit $= 120 - 95 = \rupee 25$
\item Product Q: Profit per unit $= 150 - 120 = \rupee 30$
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Step 3 — Calculate profit in April (sales in thousands of units):}
\begin{itemize}
\item P: $80 \times 25 = \rupee 2{,}000$ thousand
\item Q: $95 \times 30 = \rupee 2{,}850$ thousand
\item April total $= 2{,}000 + 2{,}850 = \rupee 4{,}850$ thousand
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Step 4 — Calculate profit in May (sales in thousands of units):}
\begin{itemize}
\item P: $70 \times 25 = \rupee 1{,}750$ thousand
\item Q: $85 \times 30 = \rupee 2{,}550$ thousand
\item May total $= 1{,}750 + 2{,}550 = \rupee 4{,}300$ thousand
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Step 5 — Total combined profit:}
$$\text{Total Profit} = 4{,}850 + 4{,}300 = \textbf{\rupee 9{,}150 thousand}$$

\textbf{Why other options are wrong:}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Option A (\rupee 8,700 thousand):} Results from incorrectly using profit per unit of P = \rupee 20 (wrong cost price of \rupee 100).
\item \textbf{Option C (\rupee 9,600 thousand):} Results from including June (where Q $<$ P) in the calculation.
\item \textbf{Option D (\rupee 8,250 thousand):} Results from using only Q's profit and ignoring P's contribution in the qualifying months.
\end{itemize}

Hence, the correct answer is \textbf{(B) \rupee 9,150 thousand}.

